TextEquiv.Unicode: The COUNTRY JOURNAL: OR, THE CRAFTSMAN.
By CALEB D'ANVERS, of GRAY'S‐INN, Eſq;
SATURDAY, FEBRUARY 19, 1742‐3.
Printed for W. WARD, at the BLACK LION in Saliſbury‐Court, Fleet‐Street.
G

REAT Oﬀence hath been taken, by certain Perſons, at the new Di‑ inion which, almo univerſally, prevails, of Hanoverians and Eng‑ liſhmen , and ſuitable Endeavours have been uſed to ſhew, that it hath no Foundation in Reaſon, and that it abounds with Dangers in the Uſe and Applica‑ tion.

Of theſe Dangers I propoſe to ſay nothing ; I hope they do not aﬀe Great Britain. If there is any Cauſe for the Diinion, it is one of the wor we have to fear ; and thoſe who gave Riſe to it may thank themſelves for the Conſequences. But as to the Foundation on which it is built, a few ſupplemental Thoughts may not be un‑ feaſonable.

I call them ſupplemental, becauſe ſo many excellent Obſervations have been made public already on this Sub‑ je ; and I think they will not be unſeaſonable, becauſe a new m——1 Packet of Poiſon is ju gone forth, under the Title of an Antidote.

Every Body allows, that Intere is the ﬁr Mover in the Projes of Princes, as well as thoſe of private Men ; but of what Kind that Intere is, hath been, generally, Matter of Diſpute. Miniers, of all Sorts, uniformly, in, that the Intere of the Cabinet is ever grafted upon That of the People. If the Voice of the motley Junto, now in the Secret, is to be depended upon, the Servants of the —— have proved themſelves to be, indeed, the Friends of the Commonwealth. But the Tree mu be known by its Fruits ; and it unfortunately happens that, in Exchange for the Millions annually levy'd, and ſquan‑ der'd, they have nothing to produce but certain annual Volumes of ingniﬁcant Treaties.

But, to wave Retroſpes for the preſent, we are par‑ ticularly told, that the Meaſure which gave Riſe to the obnoxious Diinion above ſpecify'd, is a true Engliſh Meaſure, and deſerves not to be igmatized with the Brand of H——n ; and if we require this Aertion to be made good, it is reply'd in Eﬀe, That to humble France is the fundamental Intere of England ; that to a the Queen of H— is the neare Way to humble France ; and that the neare Way to a the Queen of H—, is to take into Engliſh Pay the Mercenaries of H—r.

Now, as what we buy becomes our own, I am ready to agree, that this Meaſure is an Engliſh Meaſure. We have not only bought it, but as dear as poble, it ſeems, not one Item having been forgot, which could inﬂame the Bargain, of which the 139,313 l. Levy‐Money, for Troops already raiſed for the Service of their own Sove‑ reign, and the xteen Months to the Year, are mo notorious Inances. But, except in this one Article of the Purchaſe, I ſee no Colour for giving it any ſuch De‑ nomination.

England hath no Dominions on the Continent, conſe‑ quently was in no immediate Danger from the numerous anding Armies of France, nor from any Enterprize their mighty Monarch ſhould undertake ; and as to her Fleets, were they as formidable as when they engaged both the Engliſh and Dutch in Conjunion, oﬀ of Malaga, and aually on the Point of putting to Sea again us, I can‑ not, for my Life, imagine how theſe dear bought Mer‑ cenaries could contribute any Way to our Preſervation.

Neither had we any Call to make Acquitions on the Continent ; all our Hiories bearing witneſs, that ſuch Acquitions have ever been our Bane. God forgive our Anceors, if they were miaken in this Particular, and us, for inheriting their Prejudices ! But I am grievouſly afraid they will, likewiſe, deſcend to our Children, unleſs the Services we are now to reap from our Union with * * * * * * ſhould open out Eyes, and remove them for good and all.

But the Queen of H—, our good Ally, hath been ripp'd of one of her be Provinces, by the King of P—, another of our good Allies. Nor mu the La be outed again, nor mu the Fir be a Suﬀerer. What remains, then, but to make her Amends, at the Expence of the common Enemy ; and, as we connived, to ſay no more, at her ſaid Loſs, who but we ought to be at the Expence of repairing it ?

How far the proverbial Expreon of robbing PETER to pay PAUL, is of Authority in Politics, I leave to the great Maers in that intricate Science to determine. But, according to my glimmering Perceptions, the Intere of England is very little, if at all, concern'd on either Side. Till there is no Power on the Continent able to and in Oppotion to That of France, we have, demonrably, no other Intere to purſue there, than That of our Com‑ merce, at preſent ſo little attended to ; conſequently, till Holland , Prua , Hanover, &c. were invaded, had try'd their own Strength, and found it ineﬀeual, we were under no Obligation to exhau the Remainder of ours.

That, therefore, we made ourſelves Parties, at ſo va an Expence and Riſque, and are on the Point of be‑ coming Principals, in this troubleſome and dangerous Aﬀair, mu be owing to ſome other Intere than That of England ; at lea it mu be ſo preſumed, till we are furniſh'd with better Lights than thoſe we have been hi‑ therto favour'd with.

It is apparent enough, that, not long ago, the Interes of England, and thoſe of mo of the Princes of Germany, were totally oppote, if not irreconcileable. The Gran‑ deur of the Houſe of Auria, which was a Circumance ſo favourable to us, was a Terror to them ; and what contributed to maintain the Balance of Europe, was held fatal to That of the Empire.

With this Clue, it is, perhaps, eaſy to unravel the Meaſures taken, for many Years together, to humble that obnoxious Houſe ; and, condering the late Surrender of Silea, it may be as eaſy to account for the great Pains we are now taking to raiſe it up again.

The Balance of Europe may then be talk'd of, but there is ſome Reaſon to fear the Balance of Germany is mo con‑ der'd ; and ſurely, if it he allow'd me, as I think it mu, that H— is rather more concern'd in That, than E—d, the Diinion above hinted at, is not with‑ out a very ſolid Foundation.

But ſhould we take it for granted, that, in aing the Queen of H———, the greater Balance was only attended to, and the leſs, not ſo much as thought of, it will thence follow, that the more eﬀeual we render'd that A‑ ance, the more eﬀeually we ſerved our Country ; where Money is become a ſcarce Commodity, and Oeconomy is ſo much wanted, that it deſerves to be held, of all poli‑ tical Virtues, the ſupreme.

But, if one Half of the Money which the Meaſure under Conderation is to co us, had been advanced to the Queen of H———y, it ſeems ſhe would have been, to the full, as well aed, and we had been 700,000 l. in Pocket, which, in much belter Times, would have been thought no inconderable Saving.

When, therefore, we come to conder at whoſe In‑ ance this Meaſure took Place, by whom it was enforced, with what Circumances it was attended, and who were to be the Gainers, 'tis impoble for an impartial Mind not to think, that the ſaid Diinion, however miſrepreſented by thoſe principally aﬀeed by it, was well founded, nor to do Honour to him who ﬁr made it.
It is well known to the World, that, when a certain great Minier of former Times was aſk'd, How it was poble for him to diſpatch ſuch a Variety of Aﬀairs, he reply'd, By doing one at a Time.
Now, whether the War with Spain was a right, or a wrong Meaſure, (for I ſuppoſe the Junto are not yet agreed upon that Head) it was certainly the one Thing

needſul to be diſpatch'd, if the Intere of Great Britain had been eadily purſued. For, if it was a wrong Meaſure, all our Addreſs ſhould have been employ'd to bring it to an honourable Period ; and, if a Right, all our Strength, to procure us both Indemniﬁcation and Revenge.

But neither of theſe Ends ſeem, as yet, to have been attended to, unleſs in Subordination to many others, which will not admit of any Compariſon with Regard to the In‑ tere of Great Britain. We now ſuﬀer the War to languiſh, mo ſhameſully, while we labour under all the Diﬃcul‑ ties attending it, and we make no Advances towards a Peace, though the Advantages of a good one were never more neceary.

And, while in this deplorable Situation, our Land In‑ tere eat out with a Four‐Shilling‐Tax, which there is Reaſon to fear will be perpetual, our Poor‐Rates higher than ever they were known in the Memory of Man, our Manufaures in Ruins, and our Merchants groaning under all the Diſcouragements (I am loth to make Uſe of a ſeverer Expreon) poble, we needleſsly, madly, deſperately provoke a Land‐War ; which we have nothing to do with ; which we are not able to ſupport, without mortgaging ourſelves, as well as our Lands and Revenues ; and by which it is impoble WE ſhould be Gainers.

The Sea is our acknowledged Element, for Intere, Strength and Glory ; and if there is this apparent Neceſ‑ ty to humble France, we ſhould have attack'd her in her weake and mo ſenble Part, her Trade and Navigation. To a Degn of that Nature, there would not have been one negative Voice in Great Britain ; becauſe there could have been no Diſpute, whether the Intere of Great Britain, or Hanover, was mo concern'd in it. Neither were the mo plauble Pretences wanting to authorize ſuch a Meaſure ; witneſs the hoile Appearance of their Squa‑ drons, both in the We‐Indies and the Mediterranean, in Concert with our open and avow'd Enemies the Spaniards ; Inſults of ſuch a notorious Nature, that no M——y, who made the Intere of Great Britain their governing Prin‑ ciple, could have overlook'd, or would not have reſented with the whole Force which God and Nature had put into our Hands.

That, therefore, they ſhould give out, that to humble France was the chief Intere of Great Britain ; and yet, in Contempt of the Experience of pa Times, and the Common‐Senſe of the preſent, that they ſhould per in taking the Bull by the Horns ; That is to ſay, in attacking the Enemy in his full Strength, again the Inclinations of the People, when they might hurt him much more grie‑ vouſly, by aing agreeable to the Inclinations of the People, aﬀords ſuﬃcient Grounds, to conclude, That the Intere of Great Britain has NOT been eadily purſued, and that the Diinion of Hanoverians and Engliſhmen, ought ever to be kept up, as long as there is the lea Reaſon to fear, that the Wealth and Strength of the one are exhaued, to enrich and aggrandize the other.
This Day are publiſh'd, In ONE VOLUME in Oavo, REMARKS on the HISTORY of ENGLAND.
By HUMPHREY OLDCASTLE, Eſq;

FOREIGN AFFAIRS.

Turin, February 1. The la Letters from Toulon ad‑ viſe, that Admiral Navarro has received Orders a ſecond Time to return to Cadiz with the Spaniſh Fleet, and is preparing to obey them ; but that ſeveral French Men of War will ſet ſail along with him, becauſe they reaſonably apprehend ſome Inſult from the Engliſh.
